Now let me look more carefully at the `remove` method. I can see the issue! In the case of removing from a 3-element map, the code has a bug where it returns the wrong old value in certain cases. Here's the issue:

For example, when removing `key3` from a 3-element map, it returns `value3` (correct), but when removing `key2`, it incorrectly returns `value3` instead of `value2`.

Let me look at the exact problematic parts of the remove method:

```java
case 3:
    if (hash3 == hashCode && key.equals(key3)) {
        Object old = value3;  // correctly returns value3
        hash3 = 0;
        key3 = null;
        value3 = null;
        size = 2;
        return old;
    }
    if (hash2 == hashCode && key.equals(key2)) {
        Object old = value3;  // BUG: should be value2!
        hash2 = hash3;
        key2 = key3;
        value2 = value3;
        hash3 = 0;
        key3 = null;
        value3 = null;
        size = 2;
        return old;  // returns old value3, not value2!
    }
    if (hash1 == hashCode && key.equals(key1)) {
        Object old = value3;  // BUG: should be value1!
        hash1 = hash3;
        key1 = key3;
        value1 = value3;
        hash3 = 0;
        key3 = null;
        value3 = null;
        size = 2;
        return old;  // returns old value3, not value1!
    }
```

